The plant doesn’t heal us. Only we can do that. I’m of the opinion rather it helps us to hold space so that we can take the actions we need to heal ourselves more deeply and fully. My c@nn@ use for over a decade felt better than what I had been feeling, but in reality, I wasn’t ready to take the next steps on my healing path. The plant allowed me some peace while I got there, but the healing is far from over. Always grateful for my plant friends helping me on the journey. ✨

I mean, if it makes you feel better and function better, what’s the real diff?? 🙃 I 💜 therapy. I also💜 using medicinal 🪴plants, herbs, and the like, to bring about shifts in my consciousness that my 🧠 just won’t allow otherwise. I went to my first Burning Man this year. I knew it would change me but I had no idea how much. I learned a lot about the community, but even more about myself. 💫From the amazing people at my camp⛺️ to the sunrise bike rides 🌅 breathtaking art 🎨 radical life lessons🌀 dust storm parties 😶‍🌫️ and leaning into a challenging but inspiring community of creatives, I found my way home. 💖

This experience taught me that life is what you make it and even when I don’t know which way camp is, or if I’ll beat the dust cloud, or how to find that one friend way out on the playa somewhere, I always have my own back and I am safe. 

I was grateful to leave just as the rains began to sprinkle in, and I left knowing I would forever be better because of this experience. To everyone I encountered that showed me grace, taught me something, or shared a little of their light, thank you. 🙏🏻💜🌀✨

Expected family time, like around the holidays, isn’t easy for me, and I know I’m not alone in this. The constant triggers from off-handed comments, feeling of disconnection, and family member’s inability to look at the hard stuff makes me question why I keep showing up. 

But since I’ve been steadfast in my healing path, I now know to only show up when I am ready, with tools in place to manage the big emotions, and the healed parts of me get to keep me safe. I’ve spent the last few years away from my family to take time I needed to heal, and while it’s not easy, as I focus on repairing my own heart, I find that I understand more of why they can’t show up for me. While it doesn’t make it any easier, it does allow me to cherish the precious moments with them while I’m here, odd as it feels.

The work is demanding, but it is worth it. ✨

✨ I’ve spent a lot of my life strategically moving in ways that felt safe, expected, acceptable, like what I should be doing. And it often didn’t feel right, or felt frustrating, like I was captive to norms which I did not subscribe to. 

As I’ve gotten older and learned to 
•trust myself more
•stop holding onto these ideas that I’ve got to make others happy bc (heaven forbid) they judge me and I’m found wanting in some way
•let others have their opinions about me/my actions, and not worry about it so much bc they aren’t living my life, nor I theirs 

The thing is, we all judge and get judged by others on our path, about our path, whether we mean to or not. And I believe it’s -part- of the path to let go of both sides of that as much as possible and to the best of our ability. In that letting go is great power and even greater freedom to create the life you want and deserve. And who wouldn’t be happy about that?!

Here’s to these words to live by bc when you apply them, it really is quite amazing. ✨Love ya’ll
